One of the most effective ways to innovate is to ask:

“What is the mechanism, independent of the material it’s made from?”

Don’t copy the organism—copy the invariant.

For Turritopsis dohrnii, the mechanism isn’t “be a jellyfish.” It’s something more abstract:

When degradation exceeds a threshold, revert to a previously validated developmental state, preserve useful information, reorganize, then regrow.

That generalizes remarkably well.

